/*
 * transcode.c - GE-120 card-reader column transcoder.
 *
 * Empirically derived from the oracle pair:
 *   software/DUMP1/funktionalcpu.cap  (228 cap cards; first 114 have hex data)
 *   software/DUMP1/funktionalcpu.bin  (9120 bytes = 114 cards × 80 columns)
 *
 * Derivation methodology:
 *   The .cap file stores each column as a 13-bit value (cap parser masks to
 *   0x1FFF).  Using all 9120 (card, column) pairs from the first 114 cap cards
 *   and the corresponding 9120 .bin bytes as oracle output, a 13-bit→byte map
 *   was built.  Result: 267 distinct 13-bit input values, 0 collisions, 18
 *   distinct non-space output values.  All remaining 7925 table entries
 *   default to 0x20 (GE space / blank column).
 *
 * Bit assignments (as observed in the cap data):
 *   bit  0  = Hollerith row 0  (10-punch / zone-0 / digit-0)
 *   bit  1  = Hollerith row 1  (digit 1)
 *   ...
 *   bit  9  = Hollerith row 9  (digit 9)
 *   bit 11  = Hollerith row 11 (zone X / 11-punch) [not seen in oracle]
 *   bit 12  = Hollerith row 12 (zone Y / 12-punch)
 *
 * Known non-space mappings (18 entries):
 *   0x0001→0xF0 ('0'), 0x0002→0xF1 ('1'), 0x0004→0xF2 ('2'),
 *   0x0008→0xF3 ('3'), 0x0010→0xF4 ('4'), 0x0020→0xF5 ('5'),
 *   0x0040→0xF6 ('6'), 0x0080→0xF7 ('7'), 0x0100→0xF8 ('8'),
 *   0x0200→0xF9 ('9'), 0x0003→0x4C ('<'), 0x0005→0x7C ('@'),
 *   0x0009→0x7B ('#'), 0x0041→0xE7 ('X'), 0x0081→0xE8 ('Y'),
 *   0x0101→0x6B (','), 0x0201→0xBA (special), 0x1001→0x4E ('+').
 *
 * TC_BINARY mode: returns low 8 bits of the column value unchanged.
 *
 * CAVEAT (character code): the TC_NORMAL output values above are EBCDIC
 * (digits 0xF0-0xF9, 'X'=0xE7, ','=0x6B) because they were fit to the
 * externally-supplied funktionalcpu.bin, which is an EBCDIC rendering of the
 * deck. They are NOT the GE machine's documented internal character code. The
 * real GE-120 card transcoder (CRZ[2] §5.3, "Table 3 — IBM card code and
 * Internal GECB code equivalent") converts IBM/BULL card punches to the GE-100
 * internal graphic set (digit '0'=0x40, 'J'=0xA1, …; APS Reference Manual
 * Figure 3), which is what gdis uses for DB-comment glyphs (see docs/ISA.md
 * §2.1). This mismatch only affects hypothetical NORMAL-mode text reads;
 * program loading uses by-pass/COLBIN (TC_COLBIN), whose B2R map is
 * document-confirmed.
 */

